x4freetext: 100 MeV proton beam on lithium target.
Beam monitoring by Faraday cup and TFBC.
Neutron beam spectrum on Fig.2. consists of:
-peak centered at energy slightly lower than the
-low-energy tail, contains about 50% of total number
Low-energy neutrons were rejected. Intensity of
the resulting 96-MeV neutron beam is of order of
1.E+4 neutr/cm**2/sec. Neutron beam was collimated to
60 microSR solid angle. Beam spot at about 10m from
lithium target has diameter of 8 cm.
- proton detection with 35 MeV energy threshold in
- proton energy measured using 24 CsI(Na) detectors
- proton trajectory calculated with two drift chambers
- count rate increased using a sandwiched multitarget
- events associated with 96 MeV neutrons from the
beam are selected using a time-of-flight technique
2 mm thick plastic scintillators as triggers for
- detection of proton and light charged particles
(up to A=4) in the angular range 20-160 degrees
- array of eight Si-Si-CsI(Tl) telescopes placed in a
- particle identification using dE-dE and dE-E
- angular resolution given by opening angle of
- events associated with 96 MeV neutrons from the
beam are selected using a time-of-flight technique
- 50 microns reaction target placed at the chamber
Fission detector composed of thin-film breakdown
of iron,lead,uranium. CH2 target as monitor.
